While impacts from urban areas such as pollution and eviction likely have a negative impact on this species, their negative impacts may be offset by positive ones of additional roosts and new foraging opportunities.  The overall range of the big brown bat has undoubtedly increased with urbanization.  Reproductive success has likely risen as well from those found in natural roosts due to the benefits of warmer roosts allowing young to reach volancy faster and from increased prey availability resulting from surrounding agricultural activities.

The lack of information regarding distribution and landscape scaled population estimates makes for a high degree of uncertainty in my estimates. FYI: I used population densities measured at talus slopes in western Virginia and a rip-rap covered dam in NH, and assumed similar numbers occur elsewhere in the range. I also assumed that most rock outcrops within the range have M. leibii present. But we lack sufficient information to be able to generate population estimates because much of the range probably has unsuitable habitat.

Because this species is often associated with canyonlands in close proximity to water resources, particularly rivers, across the Western US, the threat of water impoundment was considered serious given its ability to remove large stretches of both roosting and foraging resources.

Currently only a small proportion of the species occupies urban/suburban roosts. However, if climate change, hurricanes, and/or inappropriate fire management in natural areas reduces availability of natural roost trees, bats may move to urban/suburban roosts such that a much larger proportion of remaining bats are in built environments. This in turn could drastically change threat scope and severity. A single widespread hurricane across south Florida could completely change the threat rankings.

Note that there was an error in the system. I have a screenshot of it to send you if useful. The threat Excess Energy showed up as it should for Scope but for Severity this was listed as air-borne pollutants.

Because this is a migratory species it is difficult to assess risk without considering threats in Mexico. Suitable roost sites and foraging habitats are uncommon in the US compared to Mexico.  When evaluating threats I primarily focussed on the one major roost site in the US in a national park. Because they rely so heavily on the agave in the Chisos Mts where they roost, anything that destroys that resource (fire, feral hogs, invasive plants) could have a severe impact on this colony.

This was a very challenging task from estimating population size to population affected by the various threats which is why I often chose 50% confidence in my answers. However, I believe the pallid bat is the #1 species most vulnerable to changes in the environment and general human land use practices with such specialized terrestrial foraging needs combined with and an affinity for and vulnerability when roosting in man-made structures where they are potentially regularly faced with disturbance, vandalism, exclusions and extirpation/extermination.

column550:
When I started surveying Maca in CA in 1968, the species was absence from about 30% of its CA range in the western counties due to urbanization, roost disturbance and foraging habitat destruction. As a result of an USGS Species at Risk Grant to BCI in 2000, I visited all the largest known and historic roosts, and then surveyed around the known range perimeter. I feel that I defined the range of Macrotus in the US as of 2003 in the report submitted to BCI. Yet the range of the bat that we are using for this assessment is comprised of all the old museum records where the species does not now occur nor does the appropriate habitat. Since the range of the bat determines the population size and the basis for trends, it is important to use the current known range. 
The reason for past declines (foraging habitat and roost destruction) are still ongoing, especially as cities within the Sonoran Desert expand (along the Lower Colorado River, Tucson and Phoenix). With the increased population exploring around the city perimeters and beyond,  mine closures for human safety are increasing. Depending on the price of gold and other metals, renewed mining in historic districts impacts Maca roosting in the mines. Mine closures are still conducted at times without adequate surveys for bats. 
A threat to Maca that has not yet been quantified is the effect of solar farms, many within the range of Maca and some very close to known roosts. These remove foraging important habitat, and depending on the angle of the panels at night, could also attract bats when the echo suggests water or may not even be returned to the bat (i.e. no obstacle present), and this could result in bat impacts. Bat surveys are not required post-construction, and for Macrotus (a slow flying surface foraging bat) this could be analogous to wind turbine fatalities for aerial insectivores.

Ive been working on this species for about 20 years and I do not consider myself as having a great degree of confidence in the population level  impacts of many of these threats.  I do know that Pd has been devastating, and in the shorter term (10-20yrs), drastically overshadows all others in its impact.
Mining, desert recreational activities, desert solar, desert Ag (Imperial Valley, CA), drought/temp extremes the main threats in the US

The distribution map is wrong because it is including specimens in collections whose taxonomy has not been updated.  The yellow bats in the west are L. (Dasypterus) xanthinus. Clearing for the border wall in south Texas is impacting the historical core of the species distribution in the US by removing roosting habitat (palms) and wind energy development in south Texas is killing yellow bats. However, this is hopefully slightly offset by the fact that over the last 20 years their distribution has expanded and they are being found further north and are using urban areas for roosting (especially if there are palms whose fronds are not trimmed). The number of yellow bats submitted to the Texas Department of health for rabies testing has increased over the past 15 years indicating that Southern Yellow bats are increasingly being encountered in urban or suburban areas.

"Other Ecosystem Modifications" is where I evaluated loss or modification of roosting habitat, either through mine remediation by complete closure or gates as I don't believe we have much data on how this species responds to gates

I included WNS under  8. Invasive & Other Problematic Species, Genes, & Diseases. Biggest threats I see to the species are forest management and wildfire (loss of habitat), WNS, climate change. This species likes using large snags (25 inch diameter at breast height) and these roost trees are hard to replace post wildfire or logging operation. Some effects of human development are also possible although this species will use human structures for roosting.

Vulnerable to desert recreational activities which result in unnatural and extensive fires in palm groves, temp rise in desert environments, and tree trimming practices in suburban areas where the bat has been 'invading' in recent decades. Review Constantine 1998 CA bat range extension paper to see extent of population range extension in suburban southern California.
natural systems modifications covers snag removal, mine closures and gates, which Idph may not tolerate

I think Tadarida is likely to be affected by climate change leading to range expansion, but I think this is likely to increase population size overall rather than have a negative effect.

It is difficult to evaluate this species only in one country as it is migratory.  It will be important to factor responses from both Mexico and the U.S. and the fact that breeding occurs in one country and birthing can occur in both.

Assessed potential impacts from WNS in Invasive Species category; although O'Shea, Cryan & Bogan found that Myoc could be an early warning indicator of WNS in southwestern regions, I ranked WNS relatively low in Scope and Severity due to Myoc's tendency to roost in trees and rock crevices.

We still have a very limited understanding of how many of the listed threats influence Eumops floridanus currently and into the future. Further, it is unclear how each of these threats will change within Florida in the next 15 years based on the economy and politics. Thus, there remains a large amount of uncertainty in estimates of the scope and severity of various threats on the Eumops floridanus population. This was a difficult exercise but illustrates the importance of collecting more data to assess the status and threats facing this species.

If this species is restricted to the Florida Keys as it has been thought to since its first documentation within the US in 1994, then the entire population (within the US) faces extreme threats from climate change (sea level rise and habitat alteration, temperature increases, and severe tropical storms). If it is also present on the mainland of Florida (as has been recently suggested but not confirmed) and/or is able to move north in response to climate change threats, then the species will have greater resiliency against climate change and other threats associated with the islands.

There are many data gaps for this species, especially range-wide population estimate and trend, due to its patchy distribution and relatively small colony sizes. The paucity of population data makes it particularly challenging to assess the status of this species.

The primary (known) threat to hoary bats is mortality due to wind turbines. A recent paper (Frick et al. 2017) suggested the North American population is likely to experience a 90% population decline over 50 years based on likely population parameters and observed mortality, which corresponds to a 4.5%/year decline. However, this does not incorporate rapid build-out of the North American Wind Energy industry, nor does it consider cumulative effects of other threats. This estimate is therefore most likely to underestimate the true population decline, especially when projecting future declines. Hoary bats as a percent of total fatalities at wind energy facilities appears to be rapidly decreasing for at least some existing wind energy facilities (i.e., in Alberta), which raises the possibility that the population is collapsing in these affected regions. Hoary bats have among the largest range and longest migration distances of any terrestrial mammal, and available evidence suggests there is a single panmictic population across North America. Given their long-distance movements, the entire North American population is likely experiencing similar threats and population pressures. Although wind energy facilities cover a relatively small amount of the land base, most of the population is likely to fly close enough to these facilities to potentially be attracted to turbines. Among the other threats to hoary bats, agricultural intensification and insecticides (which reduce insect prey) are among the primary threats. The effect of climate change is mostly unknown, and there is particular uncertainty with how it will affect hoary bat through risks such as wildfire (such as during hibernation in California and elsewhere).
Other effects of climate change could be a miss-match of migration timing and food resources relied upon en-route or arrival at summer / wintering grounds when conditions are not yet favorable

CHME in San Diego County is exclusively an urban/suburban bat roosting in temporary situations in man-made structures and feeding at landscape/planted nectar plants and perhaps hummingbird feeders. There has been no evidence that it uses natural cave roosts or native plants here unlike probably in most of its range. Due to its specialized roosting and foraging needs and the need for these 2 features (caves and nectar plants) to be in relative proximity to one another (even if telemetry reveals long distance foraging bouts), it would seem to be a species vulnerable to habitat alterations from human land use as well as natural factors such as climate change.

All things considered, this species is moderately tolerant of human development/activities except in highly urbanized areas - and its range is expanding in the Midwest and mid-Atlantic Coast.  Not a species of concern at this moment in my opinion.
many of the potential risks to this species are unknown and lack empirical data to substantiate or dispel the effects of these threats

1. Island geography doesn't lend itself to continental range approach. Unique isolated populations on each island of likely different sizes, and each island population faces threats with different scopes thus severities.
2. Threats are poorly known for the species across it's island range. A few threats stand out because the associated mortality is observable - such as collisions with wind turbines, cars, barbed wire fencing. Threats such as disease, effects of local pesticide/rodenticides, and predation have not been studied.
3. It is assumed that large scale habitat loss (conversion of almost all forests to plantation agriculture and heavy ranching) contributed to general decline of the species on many islands prior to 1970's.

column550: The Hawaiian hoary bat is a unique species in a unique situation unlike almost any other. Because its full range is an island archipelago with islands geographically isolated from each other, it may not be appropriate to evaluate at statewide/country levels. Current and continuing research is pointing to genetically isolated population within islands that are vulnerable to extirpation from any number of threats. This will very likely continue to be refined in the several years and reevaluation of the state of this species may be appropriate and necessary.

column550: I think it is important to remember that this species is often mis-identified as Little Brown Myotis (via morphology and use of buildings in mixed roosts). This may lead to poor understanding of habitat use, impacts, etc. Mixed roosts of Yuma and Little Brown myotis results in poor tracking of abundance for example, as these two species are not well differentiated, if at all (eg, in emergence counts). The same comment applies to Little Brown Myotis and although I am not likely to review that species for Canada, it should be noted that in BC where these two species are commonly found in the same buildings or bat boxes, they are confused and I'd offer that in most cases the assumption is made that the species present in them in Little Brown myotis although in fact on close inspection, mixed roosts are usually >80% Yuma myotis. As the only two aquatic "skimming" species in the west, I would propose both species generally face the same threats, including the reduced prey availability in urban and rural areas where BTI is used, though no studies have been done on this that I am aware of.

In BC Fringed Myotis is widespread along the Okanagan, Boundary, Thompson regions, and is found along the Fraser River in BC all the way from the coastal mouth (Coastal Fringed Myotis) through to Williams Lake in the north. This bat is also found in the Trail - Creston - Cranbrook areas, and is suspected in the Tobacco Plains area east of Cranbrook. This is at least 26,000km2 range in BC.  It is also known from SW Saskatchewan (acoustic records only to date). I think the biggest issue with this species might be that folks aren't always looking for it in acoustics or capture. In the former, it can be mistaken as Townsend's Big-eared bat or even Long-eared Myotis, and in the latter, it can be mistaken as Long-eared Myotis if capturers are not looking for the fringe. Most confusing is the hybridization that is clearly happening in a low level between Long-eared Myotis and Fringed Myotis. We have captured 2 confirmed hybrids in SW BC (confirmed by genetics, morphology and acoustics), and several more have been suspected. Unfortunately young of the year Long-eared Myotis can have a bit of a fringe that can make telling these two species, and potential hybrids, difficult.

There may be a lag time over the next several years while maps and biologists catch up on the taxonomy. Myotis keenii is now synonymous with Myotis evotis (Lausen et al. 2019) and thus all keenii and evotis range maps need to be MERGED. 
re: Additional threat I added in about the pheromone traps. There is growing evidence (photos and anecdotes from foresters) that this species is found trapped in beetle pheromone traps in forests of BC - they may be attracted by the sounds of the trapped insects - they are unable to escape. A recent campaign by myself and others in BC may help moving forward it is not certain how widespread a problem this is and if preventative measures will be taken (we have suggested screening over the tops of the traps to exclude large bi-catch like gleaning bats).

Note that this species in Canada west of the Rocky Mntns is being considered M. melanorhinus by the Batnames.org taxonomic authority. There is urgency for an appropriate genetics study (ie better genetic markers to use including both mtDNA, nuclear, population genetics in addition to phylogenetic, and widespread sampling) to determine if the small-footed bats across western Canada are actually two different species.
In Canada the range of western small-footed myotis on the west side of Rocky Mntns extends from Maple Ridge near the mouth of the Fraser River, up the Fraser to as far as Williams Lake. They are also found across the Thompson, Okanagan and Boundary regions and are thought to be in small numbers in the Trail and possibly Tobacco Plains areas  near the US border. In Alberta they are found as far north as the Red Deer River, a little further west than Lethbridge, and they extend into Saskatchewan an unknown extent. In the prairies they reside almost exclusively along river valleys and my PhD thesis (Lausen 2007) looked at their landscape genetics in AB and MT and found they do not breed among river systems, with limited male dispersal, and high male philopatry. This patchiness and seemingly low migration rates I believe adds to their vulnerability to any catastrophic events such as floods, mudslides, dams which could wipe out complete lineages/haplotypes.

Pallid bat has a small range in Canada - extending from the US border near Osoyoos BC up to Vernon, possibly a bit further north. Vineyards are the biggest threats, as native grasslands are converted, and irrigation practices can often create traps for them (e.g. Big-O pipes have been known to be found with pallid bats at the bottom of them, likely attracted in by distress calls from the first bat that has accidentally slide down into one). We know due to research out of Jesse Barber's lab in Idaho that noise can be deterimental to foraging success by this species, and there are major roads and highways throughout the foraging area of these bats, in addition to fans and purposeful noise that is generated in cooling crops and deterring predators in summer growing months. For summaries of this species in Canada and its status:
http://www.env.gov.bc.ca/wld/documents/recovery/rcvrystrat/pallid_bat_rcvry_strat110908.pdf
https://wildlife-species.canada.ca/species-risk-registry/virtual_sara/files/plans/rs_pallid_bat_e_final.pdf
In addition to what is shown on the map, COTO is also found across Vancouver Island in BC. It is our primary bat species found in low elevation mines and military bunkers across its range.

They appear to be expanding northward in Texas, but they now overlap in range with Lasiurus xanthinus, which makes species identification via morphology difficult. There are high rates of fatality for this species at wind energy facilities in southern Texas. One plant had an estimated rate of 503–984 bat per year alone.

Forestry stressors were a bit confusing because hardwood cutting is part of pulp production to balance out the fiber component with pines at the mill.  However, the extensive cutting of hardwood swamps that often have hollow boles and are infrequently replaced, occurs on a long rotation or unpredictable rotation when droughts occur and equipment can access the swamps.  Flooding of caves, perhaps due to extreme, potentially-climate-related events can create hypoxic conditions in the roost that can kill thousands of individuals and trap them within the roost.  This species is frequently found on or in transportation structures, which may be an attractive nuisance for the species, but may also provide, in many cases, stable and long-term roosts, especially on bridge superstructure over river channels.  However, bridges do need to be cleaned, painted, and replaced, but generally on a long-cycle.  Species also known from roadway culverts, both in winter and summer.  We have observed some small-scale mortality from cold snaps in culverts, which offer moderate thermal stability when compared to caves, which are highly limited in many portions of the species' range.  This species not infrequently found in barns and other structures, which can create conflict and unfriendly exclusion in some cases.  The winter patterns of this species are somewhat a mystery.

Primary threat is WNS with secondary low level threats related to roost access and disturbance and access to water. Populations appear stable but will likely be impacted by WNS. Magnitude of impacts is uncertain. Abundance is uncertain. In forested areas of the northern rockies this species is as common as the little brown bat, so may be very abundant in some areas.

column550: I used national maps to estimate scope of threats such as urbanization, agriculture, renewable energy (i.e., wind energy), roads and railroads, logging & wood harvesting, and dams and water impoundments. I included both invasive plant species and WNS in the category "Invasive nonnative/alien species/diseases" and so both scope and severity for this threat were these things taken together. Based on the Conservation Measures Partnership definition of "hunting & collecting terrestrial animals," which includes killing or trapping for control/persecution, I considered improper bat eviction/exclusion when scoring this threat and based my assessment on my experiential knowledge from working in Idaho where improper evictions/exclusions often result in the mortality of entire colonies of hundreds or up to 1000 bats, or that results in the loss of the entire reproductive output for a year when control activities are conducted in the summer and the adult females get out but nonvolant pups/juvs are trapped inside and die. I consider this a serious conservation challenge for this species in states that do not regulate wildlife control operators because Yuma Myotis is one of the primary species that uses human structures for maternity colonies. In assessing this species, I also drew on various resources including peer-reviewed literature and studies that had assessed the effects of forest management on bats, the impact of extreme temperature on Yuma Myotis (i.e., that they become heat stressed at temperatures over 40 deg C). I also reviewed heat maps of the US to assign scope for this. This species will also likely be impacted by drought because it forages over water and lactating females need a dependable free water source. I also reviewed "Bats in the Anthropocene: Conservation of Bats in a Changing World" Voigt and Kingston (editors) to find information on various threats such as roads, urbanization, and silviculture. I also considered the adaptive capacity of this species to climate change.
There is an overall lack of baseline information on this species within much of it's range.
